[1] Sri Lanka
Date: Mon 6 Jul 2009
Source: China View [edited]
<http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2009-07/06/content_11663378.htm>


The number of dengue deaths has risen to 165 while over 14 000 cases
have been reported in Sri Lanka so far from hospitals countrywide,
officials from the Department of Government Information said on Monday
[6 Jul 2009]. This represents a sharp increase as [only] 4156 dengue
cases and 85 deaths were reported for the whole year of 2008.

In a bid to control the rapidly spreading dengue epidemic, the health
authorities have decided to import Cuban bacteria to tame the virus.
The rapid rise in the level of the epidemic has forced the health
authorities to carry out an extensive public awareness campaign to
eradicate the mosquito based epidemic.

Households have been warned to keep the environment free of
mosquitoes. Those who allow the mosquitoes to breed by allowing
stagnating water face prosecution. A special hotline is available for
public information.

[Byline: Xiong Tong, Editor]

--
Communicated by:
HealthMap Alerts via ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The "Cuban bacteria" mentioned above are probably _Bacillus
thuringiensis serovar. israelensis_, an organism which produces toxins
that are insecticidal and widely used as a mosquito larvacide. Neither
the organism nor its toxins have any effect at all on dengue viruses
themselves.

The 10 Jul 2009 edition of Individual.com
<http://www.individual.com/storyrss.php?story=103611740&hash=61c34f54751de6e869713f3f04ef488a> indicates that to date there have been 170 dengue deaths and 16 179 dengue cases in Sri
Lanka.

A map of Sri Lanka can be accessed at
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/middle_east_and_asia/sri_lanka_pol01.jpg>.

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of Sri Lanka can be accessed at
<http://healthmap.org/promed/en?name=Sri%20Lanka,%20Sri%20Lanka&g=1227603&v=7,81,5>.
- Mod.TY]

