[6] Viet Nam (south)
Date: Fri 3 Jul 2009
Source: VietNamNet Bridge [edited]
<http://english.vietnamnet.vn/Health/2009/07/856258/>


Dengue fever may become [epidemic] in southern Viet Nam
-------------------------------------------------------
The Health Ministry on [2 Jul 2009] said more than 25 000 dengue fever
cases were recorded in the 1st half of 2009, including 26 deaths,
mainly children, up by 25 percent year on year.

The disease mainly developed in southern and central provinces, namely
Phu Yen, Binh Dinh, Quang Ngai, Ninh Thuan, Ba Ria, Vung Tau, Can Tho,
Hau Giang, Kien Giang and HCM City. In HCM City, some hospitals
recorded an increase of 50-70 percent of dengue fever patients since
mid June [2009].

The Preventive Health and Environment Agency's chief Dr. Nguyen Huy
Nga said that dengue fever rose because of many reasons, including
climate change. From 2000 to 2007, the number of patients increased by
4-fold compared to 1980-1989. The habit of Vietnamese people of
storing water in open tanks is also a major factor in the development
of mosquitoes and thus the spread of dengue fever [epidemics] in the
above provinces and cities.

The Health Ministry is worried that dengue fever may become [epidemic]
in the southern region in late 2009. The ministry has asked local
administrations to take measures to prevent the disease.

[Byline: Cam Quyen]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-MBDS
<promed-mbds@promedmail.org>

[At present, 25 700 cases and 26 deaths of dengue infection have been
detected in Viet Nam during 2009 with most of the cases reported from
southern provinces. There are 4649 cases and 7 deaths reported in Ho
Chi Minh City, more than 900 cases and one death in Tien Giang
province, and more than 2380 cases and 5 deaths in Soc Trang province
in 2009.

At the beginning of July 2008, 28 provinces and cities in Viet Nam had
reported more than 20 000 cases and 20 deaths which included more than
4000 cases and 3 deaths in Ca Mau province, more than 1400 cases and
one death in Tien Giang province, and more than 1900 cases in Soc
Trang province (see prior PRO/MBDS posting Dengue - Viet Nam (07)
20080708.2075).

Of note is that double infection with heteroserotypes of dengue
viruses might exist in Viet Nam, as all 4 serotypes of dengue viruses
had been detected previously.

For maps of Viet Nam with provinces, see
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/middle_east_and_asia/vietnam_admin01.jpg> and
<http://www.angelfire.com/co/hongnam/vnmap.html>.
The interactive HealthMap/ProMED-mail with direct
links to other outbreaks in Viet Nam and
surrounding countries reported on ProMED-mail and PRO/MBDS can be accessed at
<http://healthmap.org/r/008c>. - Mod.YMA]

