[7] Brazil (Rio de Janeiro)
Source: G1 (10 Jul 2009) [in Portuguese, trans. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://g1.globo.com/Noticias/0,,MUL1225713-9981,00-RIO+TEM+O+MELHOR+RESULTADO+DO+PAIS+NA+DIMINUICAO+DOS+CASOS+DA+DENGUE.html>


In the state [Rio de Janeiro, the number of dengue cases] decreased
from 246 087 cases in 2008 to 10 424 this year. People have created
resistance [develped immunity?] to the disease [infection], but
fighting it continues. According to the Ministry of Health, Rio de
Janeiro was the state with the greatest reduction in numbers of dengue
cases in Brazil.

The state Secretariat of Health reported that January to June this
year [2009], 10 424 people had the disease, versus 246 087 registered
cases during the same period of last year [2008]. The fall in [numbers
of] cases of the disease is 95 percent. According experts, the types
of [dengue] virus circulating in Rio, are the same [as those in the]
epidemic of 2008. Therefore, most of people may have created
resistance [developed immunity] to the disease. Moreover, the effort
to combat the mosquito population also contributed much to the fall in
the number of cases.

Every day [vector control] officials are going out into the streets to
inspect the houses. Each region of the city has permanent officials;
for example, some neighborhoods pay attention to them such as Cachabi
and Todos os Santos. But the officials do not always have an easy job.
Many people do not allow the professionals into their homes. "Many
people still do not allow our entry, which has made the job difficult
because we cannot go in to do the survey [of _Aedes aegypti_
infestation]," said another official.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-PORT
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Sometimes I wonder if these statements by the Ministry of Health are
the result of ignorance or a tentative, bumbling effort to deceive the
people. Dengue is a disease of fluctuating incidence, with epidemics
in some years and few cases in others. The fact we did not have an
epidemic in Rio de Janeiro in 2009 could not, necessarily, be due to
the control measures, but most likely is a result of normal
fluctuation. Within 2 or 3 years there is a considerable likelihood
that we will have another epidemic. This is the case in Brazil and in
almost all countries where dengue is endemic and epidemic. The public
deserves more accurate and honest information. - Mod.LJS]

[Without quantification of dengue virus vector mosquito presence in
houses and buildings over time, it is difficult to know how effective
the mosquito control program has been. Similarly, no data are
presented that indicate the antibody prevalence rates, and hence "herd
immunity" of the population, to the dengue virus serotypes that are
circulating currently.

[A map of Brazil showing the location of the states can be accessed at
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/americas/brazil.jpg>.
The state of Espirito Santo can be located on the
HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of Brazil at
<http://healthmap.org/r/00ub>. - Mod.TY]

