[8] Brazil (Bahia)
Date: Thu 9 Jul 2009
Source Fonte: A Regiao [in Portuguese, trans. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www2.uol.com.br/aregiao/2009/07/entry_88.html>


[Numbers of] dengue cases are beginning to decline in Bahia. The
epidemiological bulletin published by the State Department of Health
shows that the number of notifications of cases of dengue in Bahia
continues to fall. The progressive decrease in the number of patients
began in early April [2009].

In the last week of June [2009], 320 new [dengue] cases were recorded
throughout the state. Up to the beginning of April more than 1000
cases per week were reported, which contributed to the state reaching
a record [number] of dengue cases, 93 191, this year [2009]. This
represents an increase of nearly 190 percent in comparison with the
same period of 2008. This year [2009], 391 municipalities have
reported cases of dengue.

Itabuna, Ilheus, Jequie, Porto Seguro, Salvador and Feira Santana
account for 42 percent of reported dengue cases. These cities also
have the greatest number of cases of DHF.

The good news is that the index of _Aedes aegypti_ larvae is falling
steadily. In some districts of Itabuna, Ilheus & Jequie the number of
breeding sites of mosquito vectors of the [virus] fell by 50 percent.
The disease killed 56 people this year.

--
